<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://scientium.com/Commentary/Bowden_Essays/startrip/starship/tau.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <br>
<br>
The TAU was a Jet Propulsion Laboratory design. Planned as an interstellar percursor mission, it can travel at approximately 20 A.U. per year (3 trillion meters per year, or about 95 kilometers per second). <br>
The TAU uses a nuclear reactor to generate about 150 kilowatts of electricity. This is used to expel a stream of charged ions taken from an inert reaction mass. Usually this mass is xenon. Exhaust velocities are about 70 kilometers per second. The boost phase is approximately ten years long. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tmayes1999>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 204<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/26/03 3:52:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=251.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Powered Interstellar rocket type star probes.</span><hr size=1> 1. A nuclear electric ion rocket  propelled  star probe was designed by  Jpl in the 1980s that could reach .0133 C and it would take about 400 years to reach the nearest stars.<br>
Price tag is at least 500,000,000 dollars.<br>
This is 100% feasible right now.IT may be too slow for practical starflight but nuclear electric ion and plasma<br>
drive  rockets can revolutionize interplanetary spaceflight for both crewed and robotic missions right now<br>
2. A solar sail powered star probe that uses only natural<br>
sunlight for  its thrust has been designed that can reach about .015 C, and it can reach the nearest stars in<br>
about  350 years flight time. The price tag is least<br>
20,000,000  dollars. This star probe  design if lasers or<br>
 masers are used to replace the natural sun light, can accelerate up nearly the velocity of light.It is cheapest,and fastest, and very feasible . That is why Nasa has chosen this design for our future robot interstellar probes to nearby stars, which will be launched later in this century.*<br>
3. Orion or Deadalas class nuclear pulse rockets that  can reach the nearest stars with a flight time of about 40 years<br>
have been designed. The price tag is at least 50,000,000,000<br>
dollars per ship for this design. If a human crewed star flight were tried in this century it would probably use a Deadalas <br>
or Orion class nuclear fusion pulse drive. It peak cruising<br>
velocity would be about .10 C which is  (1/10th of light velocity) This is 100% feasible right now.<br>
4. Matter-antimatter annhilation powered Pion rockets<br>
have been designed that can reach the nearest stars<br>
with a flight time of between 6 years and 9 years. <br>
5.At present antimatter costs 10,000,000,000 dollars per milligram. Even if the costs were reduced to 1,000,000 <br>
per milligram it would cost 1,000,000,000,000 dollars to get<br>
 1 single  kilogram of antimatter. An interstellar pion rocket<br>
that carried a crew would need 100s to thousands of tons of antimatter if they are mixed equally in a pion rocket.<br>
6. For crewed star missions warp drive is theorecticly possible<br>
using the Albueirre warp theory of 1996 , but this probably  can  never be ever achieved in practice <br>
7.  Laser/ maser light sailing is impractical, for human crewed starflights, because of the enormus energy requirements<br>
but it is very practical for low  mass pioneer/ voyager<br>
style robot star probes<br>
<br>
8. If you want to have any credible hope of accelerating a human crewed starship to much more the 1/10th of light velocity, it will probably  be necessary to use nuclear electric propulsion ion or plasma drive interstellar ramjets (Rairs) to do this.<br>
